To be specific for people that might run into this, this is the workaround: Don't recreate your contextMenuBuilder on each build if you don't have to (use an instance method instead of an inline function).

When setState is called, the build method gets called again, and a new contextMenuBuilder is passed (even though it does the same exact thing as the last one). SelectableText sees that contextMenuBuilder has changed and rebuilds it, causing the flash.

This will also happen with other EditableText-based widgets, like TextField and CupertinoTextField.

I think there might be something that we can do to fix this. It seems like it's possible to remove and re-insert an OverlayEntry into an Overlay in one frame without any flash. I wonder if it's just the fade animation that is making this flash obvious.

Related: https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/142763

